<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Bidding To Regain Place as Far East Finance Center </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1203144594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1249 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1203144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 12 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai authorities 
have decided to restore the original shape of the financial 
street in The Bund in the 1930s in a bid to turn the city into a 
financial center in the Far East, a senior official said here 
today. 
  Wu Bangguo, secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Committee of 
the Chinese Communist Party, said that government offices 
located in The Bund have begun moving out. 
  The office building of the municipal government will be 
leased out through bidding, said Wu, who is here attending the 
annual session of the National People's Congress. He invited 
overseas investors and bankers to tender bids. 
  According to Mayor Huang Ju, all the proceeds from the 
bidding will be used for local infrastructure construction. 
  In the 1930s, Shanghai served as a financial center in the 
Asia-Pacific region. Then some 130 high-rises housed in The 
Bund major Chinese and foreign banks and consortiums. 
  Now, government departments concentrate in The Bund. The 
building of the municipal government used to house the head 
office of the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation. 
  A new company has been set up in Shanghai to handle matters 
related to moving and bidding. 
  Though the offer for leasing the municipal government 
building will exceed 100 million U.S. dollars, a number of 
investors have expressed their interest. The new site of the 
municipal government building will be in the People's Square in 
downtown Shanghai. 
  The Municipal Bureau of the Space Industry moved out of The 
Bund in December, earlier than any other government agencies. 
The bureau's building now serves as the site of the National 
Foreign Exchange Trading Center. 
  Shanghai now has 30 branches of foreign-funded banks. Last 
week the Citibank of the United States moved its Asian head 
office from Hong Kong to Shanghai. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3068 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi051_o_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-051 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Country's Largest Bonded Zone Performs Well </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1303150994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1354 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1303150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, March 13 (XINHUA) -- Waigaoqiao bonded 
zone in Shanghai, the earliest and largest in China, has been 
operating well since the beginning of this year, a local 
official said here recently. 
  Last month 30 projects won approval in the zone, involving 
an 
investment of more than 16.9 million U.S. dollars, according to 
Fan Shuming, spokesman for the zone's management committee. 
Fourteen of the 30 projects are foreign-funded ones. 
  During January and February, the zone imported and exported 
more than 54.3 million U.S. dollars worth of commodities and 
transited 799,000 U.S. dollars worth of goods, Fan said. 
  In addition, more than 117 million U.S. dollars worth of 
products were manufactured and 4.7 million U.S. dollars worth of 
goods were stored in the zone, he added. 
  So far, the bonded zone, which was approved by the Chinese 
Government in June 1990 and went into operation last April, has 
approved 854 projects, involving an investment of more than 2.1 
billion U.S. dollars, handled over 300 million U.S. dollars 
worth of import and export commodities, 160 million U.S. dollars 
worth of transit goods, 12 million U.S. dollars worth of 
manufactured goods and over 200 million U.S. dollars worth of 
stored goods. 
  The bonded zone is planned to develop in an area of 10 sq 
km. 
  The first-phase project covered four sq km and was completed 
a year ahead of time. The second-phase project of six sq km has 
also started ahead of time, Fan said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

