<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Firms Urged To Use Taipei as Base of PRC Operations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503080794 Taipei CNA in English 0713 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503080794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 15 (CNA) -- Taiwan is in a good 
position to become a regional operations base for foreign 
companies with interests in Mainland China, a senior official 
with the Council for Economic Planning and Development (CEPD) 
said Tuesday [15 March]. 
  "To reach this goal, Taiwan should allow mainland Chinese to 
receive professional training here," said CEPD Vice Chairman 
Hsueh Chi. 
  Hsueh quoted a survey by the Japanese branch of the US-based 
consulting firm McKinsey &amp; Co. as finding that many foreign 
companies have faced language barriers and other cultural 
problems while developing mainland markets. 
  As Taiwan and Mainland China share a similar cultural 
background and use same language, hsueh said foreign companies 
can use Taiwan as bridgehead for mainland investment. 
  "Foreign enterprises can employ Taiwan market research 
experts and managers to help collect business information and 
handle investment affairs on the mainland," Hsueh noted. They 
can also send their mainland employees to their Taiwan 
headquarters for professional training, he added. 
  Mainland residents are still not allowed to receive training 
in Taiwan. Hsueh said the government should consider lifting 
the ban as soon as possible in order to improve Taiwan's 
prospects of becoming an Asia-Pacific regional operations center. 
  "Continued growth in economic exchanges across the Taiwan 
Strait is important to our bid to lure more foreign enterprises 
to set up regional operation bases on the island," he stressed. 

</TEXT>

