<DATE1>  15 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   TVB Accused of Pro-China Self-Censorship </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1503063794 Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS in English 15 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> HK1503063794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Tad Stoner] </F>
  [Text] TVB has been accused of self-censorship because of 
a decision not to show the anti-Beijing documentary Laogai: 
Inside the Chinese Gulag. Nine days before it was to broadcast 
the programme, the station replaced it in the schedules with a 
BBC Horizon documentary on tuberculosis. The station denies the 
documentary was pulled for political reasons. 
  Last night the chairman of the influential human rights 
organisation Justice, Nihal Jayawickrama, said he may refer TVB 
to the United Nations Commission on Human Rights. 
  Laogai sketches a portrait of China's nationwide network of 
so-called "reform through labour" camps -- detention centres 
where dissidents and delinquents are held, frequently without 
trial. The 50-minute documentary was scheduled for TVB's 
English-language Pearl channel on December 4, last year. At 
about the same time, TVB also decided not to screen the 
controversial one-hour BBC documentary Mao Zedong: The Last 
Emperor. The station has not screened the highly critical 
examination of the late Chinese Communist Party chairman saying 
the public was not interested. It broadcast its own production, 
Mao Fever, in December. 
  A range of community leaders, including legislators, urban 
councillors and media commentators, have accused TVB of 
self-censorship, a charge the station denies, although it has no 
plans to screen the BBC programme and Beijing has been vocal in 
its opposition to it. 
  A station spokeswoman Lily Chan, yesterday denied that 
self-censorship had motivated the cancellation of Laogai: 
Inside the Chinese Gulag. "It was purely a programming 
arrangement," she said. Cecilia Tan, the TVB controller of 
programming, said. "It's difficult to explain programming 
decisions. If you think of the number of programmes we run per 
day, during one year, it's more fair to comment on what has been 
scheduled. I would not care to comment on what has not 
appeared," she said. Veronica Chiu, the publicity manager for 
the Pearl channel, said the December 4 schedule was only 
tentative, and the cancellation had been "routine and normal". 
"There were no other political reasons," she said. 
  Jayawickrama, the chairman of Justice, called the refusal to 
show the programme "tragic". Justice is the Hong Kong chapter 
of the Geneva-based International Commission of Jurists which 
holds an advisory seat at the UN. "The problem with 
self-censorship is that it's a manipulation of information," he 
said. "It's far more dangerous than government censorship 
because nobody knows about it, and here is an institution whose 
sole rationale for existence is the dissemination of 
information. This is one of the matters that the (UN's) Human 
Rights Commission would be quite interested in. We've referred 
TVB to the commission in the past and we would do it again." 
  Another Justice member Hing-lee Wong, said TVB had done a 
disservice to Hong Kong. "I think it's ridiculous. We should 
be attacking the Government's licensing policy, and I plan to do 
something about this myself," Wong said. TVB is facing a 
mid-term review of its licence, although broadcast policymakers 
at the Recreation and Culture Branch have refused to become 
embroiled in self-censorship and scheduling disputes. 
  A Chinese dissident, Lau Shan-ching, who spent 10 years in a 
Guangzhou jail and has organised a series of private Hong Kong 
showings of Mao Zedong: The Last Emperor, said he was appalled 
by the cancellation. "TVB seems to have changed its policy with 
the intention not to make the Chinese angry because (the station 
has) expanding interests in China." A Liberal Party legislator, 
Christine Loh, said self-censorship was a serious denigration of 
Hong Kong's civil liberties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3088 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi051_w_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-051 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Business Executive Views Factors Affecting Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603122394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1140 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 16 (XINHUA) -- A business executive 
from Hong Kong said Hong Kong's future economy will be mainly 
affected by there factors: the China factor, the factor within 
Hong Kong's own economy and the international factor. 
  Liu Chi Keung, chairman of the Flow Chart International 
Holdings Ltd. in Hong Kong, said that if effective measures are 
formulated to cope with changes in these factors, "Hong Kong's 
economy will be able to maintain its stability." 
  The China factor is the most important one for maintaining 
Hong Kong's prosperity, said Liu, who is here attending the 
ongoing session of the National Committee of the Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference. 
  He said, "I think that as long as the Chinese mainland 
continues to implement the policy of reform and opening up and 
maintains the momentum of its robust economic growth, Hong 
Kong's economy will have a powerful backing and its market will 
continue to prosper." 
  The formulation and readjustment of the mainland's economic 
policies will have a significant impact on Hong Kong's economic 
expansion, he noted. 
  To this end, he said, the mainland should maintain the 
continuity of its policies, and take into consideration the 
interests of both big and small businesses in Hong Kong so that 
they will be able to gain good returns on their investment in, 
and trade between, the mainland and Hong Kong. 
  Speaking of the factor within Hong Kong's own economy, he 
said that this is crucial to Hong Kong's continued prosperity 
and stability. 
  Several big projects being undertaken in Hong Kong are, in a 
sense, spurring economic growth there during the present 
transitional period, he said. But, he added, therein also lie a 
number of hidden problems. 
  He said that under the pretext of "returning wealth to the 
people," Hong Kong's budget unveiled recently by its finance 
secretary has caused a sharp rise in the prices of buildings and 
high inflation as well. 
  Consequently, the future government of the Hong Kong Special 
Administrative Region (SAR) might face an economic slide when it 
takes over the management of Hong Kong's economy, he noted. 
  He expressed the hope that relevant mainland government 
departments should beware of man-made chaos in Hong Kong in the 
financial sector during the transitional period. 
  The future Hong Kong SAR Government should tighten control 
over the financial market in Hong Kong to enable the factor 
within Hong Kong's economy to be "sound and orderly." 
  As for the international factor, he said that Hong Kong's 
economy has become a component of the global economy. 
  Therefore, changes in the international economic environment 
will produce a major impact on Hong Kong's smooth transition and 
prosperity, he said. 
  So far as the Hong Kong stock exchange is concerned, 
hundreds 
of millions of investment dollars from Britain, Japan, the 
United States and the rest of the world are often traded there 
daily, resulting in steep ups and downs in stock prices. 
  "Such ups and downs will also have a tremendous impact on 
Hong Kong's economic growth," he pointed out. 
  For this reason, efforts should be made to prevent 
international consortiums from causing man-made fluctuations in 
stock prices, he said. 
  Furthermore, protectionism pursued by some countries, 
China's 
most-favored-nation trading status with the U.S., the resumption 
of China's membership in the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade, and entrepot trade will also affect Hong Kong's economic 
development, he said. 
  Counter-measures should be taken promptly to reduce the 
adverse effects of these factors to a minimum, he said in 
conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

