<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Criticizes UK Over Hong Kong Reform Bill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603032394 Beijing China Radio International in Japanese 
0930 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1603032394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing China Radio International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met with 
representatives and delegates from Hong Kong and Macao, who are 
participating in sessions of the National People's Congress 
[NPC] and the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference 
[CPPCC], at the Diaoyutai State Guest House yesterday. Minister 
Qian also heads the Preliminary Working Committee of the 
Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative 
Region. 
  In the meeting, the foreign minister said there is no 
question that the policy of having two systems in one nation 
will prove valid for Hong Kong. He predicted all targets 
provided in the Basic Law on the Hong Kong Special 
Administrative Region will be achieved by all means, and Hong 
Kong after 1997 will be more prosperous and developed than it is 
now. 
  Foreign Minister Qian said the sessions of the NPC and the 
CPPCC this year were held in an amicable atmosphere as a result 
of the fact that China's reform and open-door policy has been 
very effective in boosting the national economy and in 
stabilizing society and the people's lives. The day before the 
opening of the second session of the Eighth NPC, the UK 
authorities in Hong Kong turned over the second part of Governor 
General Patten's so-called Political Reform Bill to the 
Legislative Council for deliberations. This is another UK action 
aimed at breaking up PRC-UK cooperation. The UK likes to mouth 
the word cooperation, but what the country is doing with respect 
to the Hong Kong issue goes completely against what it says. He 
said, therefore, China will not entertain itself with 
unrealistic illusions any more. 
  Minister Qian said that with the PRC-UK talks forthcoming 
China had foreseen this. He recalls when he met with Douglas 
Hurd, UK secretary of state for foreign and Commonwealth 
affairs, in New York last October, he told the latter that at 
the PRC-UK talks there can come to only one of the two choices 
-- one is to come up with an agreement at the talks that will 
enable the political structural framework, which is born from 
elections conducted from 1994 to 1995, to continue after 1997; 
and the other is to fail to arrive at an agreement and the 
political structural framework created unilaterally by elections 
conducted by the Hong Kong authorities will be terminated on 30 
June 1997. 
  He added that China should secure the orderly transfer and 
long-lasting prosperity of Hong Kong in cooperation with many 
Hong Kong residents who love the fatherland and Hong Kong. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

