<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says No Increase in Military Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603034094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0323 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603034094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 16 (XINHUA)-- Chinese Foreign 
Minister Qian Qichen said here today that China's defence budget 
for 1994 has not gone up in real terms. 
  Qian made the assessment at a news conference here today. 
  China's military expenditure was 43.2 billion yuan in 1993 
and in 1994, the figure is 52 billion yuan, Qian said. 
  On the surface, there has been an increase, but inflation in 
1993 hit 13 percent. And this year inflation is expected to 
reach 10 percent. An increase in this year's military 
expenditure is to offset inflation, he said. 
  "For the Chinese military, therefore, the actual buying 
power 
has not gone up," the foreign minister said. 
  Military expenditure in 1994 accounts for 11 percent of the 
state budget, a proportion which has remained largely unchanged 
in recent years, he said. 
  And military spending accounts for less than 1.7 percent of 
the country's GNP, which actually represents a slight drop from 
last year's level. 
  In U.S. dollar terms, there is no change in the level of 
China's military spending, Qian said. 
  Compared with the military spendings of the United States 
and 
Japan, China's military spending is "a pittanc," Qian said. 
  China's central budget shows that the Chinese Government is 
concentrating its financial resources on developing its national 
economy instead of seeking to be a military power, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

