<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference on Foreign Economic Assistance Opens in Taipei </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503080694 Taipei CNA in English 0708 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503080694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 15 (CNA) -- A conference on 
international economic development assistance opened at the 
Taipei International Convention Center Tuesday [15 March] with 
some 50 local and foreign scholars and experts participating. 
  The two-day seminar was jointly sponsored by the 
International Economic Cooperation Development Fund (IECDF) and 
Chung-hua Institute for Economic Research. 
  Participants included officials from the IECDF, Foreign 
Ministry, World Bank and foreign envoys. The foreign guests 
came from the United States, France, Japan and Latin American 
countries. 
  Economic Affairs Minister P.K. Chiang said at the opening 
ceremony that the Republic of China [ROC] is dedicated to 
helping friendly foreign nations establish small and medium 
enterprises. 
  Chiang added that foreign aid is a mutually beneficial 
program which develops foreign friendship as well as boosts 
bilateral economic links. 
  Taiwan received foreign aid from the United States and Japan 
during 1970's, and now the two countries are Taiwan's major 
import sources, Chiang said. 
  Therefore, Taiwan's current economic aid to the Southeast 
Asian countries will eventually benefit Taiwan itself, Chiang 
said. 
  Chiang also said he hopes the foreign aid fund, currently 
set 
at NT [New Taiwan] $10.5 billion (US$396 million), can be 
increased to NT$30 billion (US$1.13 billion). 
  Since the government set up the IECDF in 1988 as an 
organization in charge of the ROC's economic assistance to 
friendly developing countries, a total of 17 loans worth over 
US$247 million have been approved. 
  In addition, the fund has given out technical assistance 
worth some US$11.8 million. 

</TEXT>

