<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN To Aid Primary Education in Poverty-Stricken Areas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403031994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0241 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1403031994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 14 (XINHUA) -- China and the United 
Nations (U.N.) are considering focusing their educational 
co-operation on helping China's primary education in 
poverty-stricken areas. 
  This was revealed here today by China's State Education 
Commission (SEC). 
  "Such a shift of focus in the next couple of years will be 
conducive for China to reach its goal of spreading nine-year 
compulsory education for all the children in the country by the 
year 2000," an SEC spokesman said. 
  He said the U.N. Children's Fund, Population Fund, 
Development Program and other U.N. organizations have in the 
past ten years provided China with free aid totalling 64 million 
U.S. dollars for ten educational projects. 
  At the same time, the Chinese Government put in five times 
this amount for these projects, he said. 
  The co-operation projects cover fundamental education, 
normal 
education, higher education, textbook compilation and population 
research, the official said, adding that every city and province 
in the Chinese mainland is involved in such projects. 
  The SEC spokesman said that advanced electronic devices have 
been deployed in the projects to train teachers for the 
poverty-stricken countryside. 
  Through training the principals of 1,000 primary schools in 
poor areas, their management personnel and some of the parents, 
95 percent of the eligible children in these areas have been 
enabled to go to school, he said. 
  Other aid projects include training centers for university 
management personnel, heads of primary and high schools and 
primary and secondary school teachers, he said. 
  Educators have been sent to other countries through such 
projects to receive training or attend academic conferences. 
"China's educational exchanges with world bodies and other 
countries have thus been further promoted," the SEC spokesman 
said. 

</TEXT>

