<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Investment To Be Sought at Bilateral Trade Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1503073794 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 15 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> HK1503073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By staff reporter Wang Yong: "China Wants U.S. Project </F>
Aid"] 
  [Text] China will seek American investment in about 800 
industrial and agricultural projects next month at a Washington 
conference on bilateral trade, coming less than two months 
before a U.S. decision on Chinese trade status. 
  This will be the largest promotion campaign staged by China 
in the United States in the past 15 years, the Ministry of 
Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation (Moftec) announced 
yesterday. 
  About 60 of the proposed projects will be hydraulic and 
thermal power stations that are expected to relieve China's 
electricity bottleneck, a Moftec spokesman said. 
  Another 100 projects are related to the construction of 
roads, railways, airports and wharfs. The remaining 500 fall 
into machinery, electronics, petrochemical, metallurgical, 
husbandry and forestry. 
  About 200 people from the State Council (China's cabinet), 
China Petrochemical Corporation, China North Industries Group, 
China National Petroleum Corporation and 25 provinces and cities 
will tour the U.S. for investment promotion. 
  The U.S. has become one of the top three foreign investors 
in 
China with promised capital input in more than 1,000 projects 
valued at more than $6 billion. 
  Chinese analysts predict U.S. investors will continue to 
land 
here as the two countries are apparently improving their 
economic relations. 
  And many international trade observers have predicted that 
the U.S. will extend its most-favoured-nation (MFN) status to 
China this year, which provides Chinese goods with the lowest 
tariffs. 
  China has insisted that the cancellation of MFN will 
definitely cast a pall over bilateral relations and business 
communities of both sides will be hurt. 
  President Jiang Zemin reaffirmed on Sunday in his talks with 
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher that differences in 
social systems and ideologies should not obstruct mutual 
co-operation. 
  "And the impending trade forum in the U.S. will provide a 
better chance for U.S. businesses to locate investment 
opportunities in China," the Moftec spokesman said. 
  The forum is to accompany a high-level conference in 
Washington with Chinese Foreign Trade Minister Wu Yi and U.S. 
Secretary of Commerce Ron Brown. 
  The conference and the trade forum are timed before the U.S. 
decision on MFN status in June. 
  China has managed to get the status as mutual means for the 
development of Sino-U.S. bilateral trade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

