<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports IAEA Suspends DPRK Nuclear Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703000394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1920 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703000394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, March 16 (XINHUA) -- The 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) said today it had 
suspended an inspection of the seven declared nuclear facilities 
in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK). 
  The IAEA, in a statement available here, said it had 
suspended the investigation because some "important measures 
which had been agreed were refused at the radiochemical 
laboratory in Yongbyon." 
  "As a result of this rejection, the IAEA Secretariat had to 
brief the board that the agency was not in a position to verify 
that there had been no diversion of nuclear material at the 
facility where the relevant measures were rejected," the 
statement said. 
  The IAEA team of inspectors made an inspection visit to the 
DPRK from March 1 to 15, based upon an understanding as to the 
aim and scope of the inspection reached in Vienna on February 15. 
  In an informal briefing in Vienna earlier today the team 
informed the board of governors the detailed results must await 
performance of follow-up analytical and evaluation work in 
Vienna. 
  However, the board members were informed that although many 
of the agreed inspection measures were carried out as envisaged, 
"other important measures" which had been agreed were refused. 
  According to the statement, a meeting of the board of 
governors on this subject will be held on Monday [21 March]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

