<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihuan Talks With Hong Kong, Macao CPPCC Members </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603141494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1339 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 16 (XINHUA) -- Maintaining the 
stability and prosperity of Hong Kong and Macao is the common 
responsibility of Hong Kong and Macao compatriots and the whole 
nation, a top Chinese leader said here today. 
  Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the 
Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), said it is 
necessary to be vigilant against those who, while making 
political troubles in Hong Kong, may create economic disorder 
there and hollow out Hong Kong's economy. 
  When paying a visit to Hong Kong and Macao CPPCC members, 
Li, 
who is also one of the top seven leaders of the Chinese 
Communist Party, said that, in the past decade, Hong Kong and 
Macao compatriots have made important contributions to the 
mainland's reforms, open policy implementation and economic 
development. 
  Social stability and economic development on the mainland 
have provided a reliable guarantee and powerful support for the 
prosperity of Hong Kong and Macao. The stability and prosperity 
of Hong Kong and Macao are linked closely with those on the 
mainland. The relationship has become more and more apparent 
with the approach of the date for sovereignty transfer, he said. 
  Continuously maintaining the stability and prosperity of 
Hong 
Kong and Macao is not only an issue of political principle but 
also an issue of the economic interests of Hong Kong and Macao 
compatriots and of the mainland people. 
  After China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong 
Kong and Macao, the Chinese Government will adhere to the 
principle of "one country, two systems" and deal with various 
questions of Hong Kong and Macao with a positive and prudent 
attitude, he said. 
  He said that the British side should be held entirely 
responsible for the breakdown of Sino-British talks on the 
arrangement of the 1994/95 elections in Hong Kong. 
  He alerted Hong Kong people against robbery of Hong Kong 
money in a "modern way." People should pay attention to 
economic issues as well as political ones there, he said. 
  He said that the Hong Kong British authorities, in violation 
of an understanding memorandum, have raised the costs of the new 
airport to such a high level as to be "rarely seen in the 
world." It will impose a huge financial burden on the Government 
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and its people 
after 1997, he said. 
  Questions should be raised, he said, about who get contracts 
for the airport project and who will get all the money. 
  Backed by an increasingly prosperous motherland, and through 
the concerted efforts of Hong Kong people, Li said, Hong Kong is 
certain to have a bright future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

