<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihuan Meets CPPCC Members, Chides UK on Hong Kong </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703054294 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1343 
GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1703054294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 16 Mar (XINHUA) -- Calling on members of 
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference [CPPCC] 
from Hong Kong and Macao today, Li Ruihuan, member of the 
Standing Committee of the CPC Central Committee Political Bureau 
and chairman of the CPPCC National Committee, pointed out: It 
is the common responsibility of compatriots in Hong Kong and 
Macao, and people of the whole country to maintain the stability 
and prosperity of the Hong Kong and Macao regions in the last 
few years of their period of transition. At present, we should 
especially heighten vigilance against the possibility that while 
creating political confusion, some people might try to work in 
secrecy under the cover of nice words and fashionable 
"decorations" in an attempt to empty Kong Kong's economy by 
creating chaos. 
  Li Ruihuan said: Over the past decade and more, compatriots 
in Hong Kong and Macao have made significant contributions to 
reform, opening to the outside world, and economic construction 
on the mainland. Hong Kong and Macao compatriots have made 
indelible contributions to the emergence of a situation on the 
mainland characterized by rapid economic growth and economic 
prosperity. Of course, stability and development on the 
mainland have also provided a reliable guarantee and forceful 
support for prosperity in Hong Kong and Macao. Stability and 
prosperity in Hong Kong and Macao cannot be separated from those 
on the mainland. With the approach of 1997 and 1999, this 
supplementary relationship between Hong Kong and Macao on the 
one hand and the mainland on the other will manifest itself more 
explicitly. Both Hong Kong and Macao compatriots and the people 
of the whole country should reach this consensus: It is 
necessary to closely link the stability and prosperity in Hong 
Kong and Macao with that on the mainland, to take it as our 
bounden duty to safeguard and promote stability and prosperity, 
and to do our utmost to contribute to such a cause. He said: 
Continued maintenance of stability and prosperity in Hong Kong 
and Macao is not only a political principle but also means the 
common economic interests of Hong Kong and Macao compatriots and 
of the people of the whole country. After resuming its exercise 
of sovereignty over Hong Kong and Macao, the Chinese Government 
will, vigorously and yet prudently, handle issues concerning 
Hong Kong and Macao. All should rest assured regarding this 
question. 
  Li Ruihuan pointed out: The British side must be held solely 
responsible for the suspension of Sino-British talks on the 
arrangements for the 1994/1995 elections in Hong Kong. Under 
the cover of democracy, the British side attempted to take 
advantage of its remaining years of colonial rule to create 
division and confusion in Hong Kong in a bid to hinder its 
peaceful transition, and to influence and manipulate Hong Kong's 
political situation after 1997 as much as possible. This is 
something we absolutely will not allow. We did not wish to see 
the talks break down, but it is not terrible now that they have, 
because there can only be two possibilities: You will not 
listen to what I say and I will not recognize what you do. 
After we resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong in 
1997, it is reasonable for us to end colonial rule and all 
arrangements not commensurate with the Basic Law. Regarding the 
issue of the political system, the important thing is we should 
all work together with one heart to make arrangements for work 
after 1997 to enable the Special Administrative Region's 
political framework to be formed quickly and to operate 
effectively. 
  Li Ruihuan said: What is important now is that while we are 
concerned about the political question, we must not neglect the 
economic question. In the past, the colonialists openly carried 
out plundering, but they are now using a modern method of raking 
economic benefits. Hong Kong's money belongs to the people of 
Hong Kong. If they lower their vigilance, their money will be 
hallowed out, and economic confusion will result, thus leaving a 
huge financial burden for the future government of the special 
region and for Hong Kong compatriots. This matter merits 
serious attention, and we should prevent it from happening. He 
pointed out: The Chinese Government supports the construction 
of the new airport in Hong Kong, but the British Hong Kong 
Government has raised the construction cost to an unprecedented 
level in violation of the provisions in the relevant 
understanding reached between the governments of the two 
countries. It is possible to calculate how much money is needed 
for building an airport and how much is needed for reclaiming 
land from the sea. There are examples in the world we can 
follow. As the situation in Hong Kong is special, it is 
understandable that the construction cost may be somewhat 
higher, but as the cost of construction is exceptionally high, 
one cannot help thinking: Who are the contractors? Who is 
taking away the money? 
  Finally, Li Ruihuan said: For years all of you here today 
have done a great deal in safeguarding the stability and 
prosperity of the Hong Kong and Macao areas. It is my hope that 
you will continue to work hard to make still greater 
contributions. I am convinced that with your unity and 
cooperation, and with the backing of the thriving motherland, 
Hong Kong's bright future is fully guaranteed. 

</TEXT>

