<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Unions in Foreign-Funded Firms Receive Attention </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403144194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1417 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1403144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, March 14 (XINHUA) -- Trade unions in 
foreign-funded enterprises in China are receiving growing 
attention from the Chinese Government, according to a national 
working conference on the work of trade unions in foreign-funded 
enterprises held today in north China's Tianjin. 
  A number of laws and regulations have been stipulated in 
China since 1993 and the number of trade unions in 
foreign-funded enterprises have grown a lot, participants said. 
  Trade unions have now been set up in 45 percent of the 
foreign- funded enterprises where they should be organized 
according to China's laws or regulations. In economic 
development zones, where foreign-funded enterprises are given 
some preferable policies, 60 percent of the foreign-funded 
enterprises have trade unions. 
  Trade unions mediate labor disputes and give Chinese workers 
legal knowledge and technical training. 
  Trade unions not only stimulate the production enthusiasm of 
workers and reduce labor friction but also help maintain normal 
operations of overseas investors' businesses, Yang Xingfu, vice 
chairman of the All-China Federation of Trade Unions said at the 
conference. 
  Trade unions should cooperate with foreign investors for 
better development of the enterprises while protecting workers' 
rights and interests, he said. 
  Trade union leaders from Tianjin, Beijing, Shanghai, 
Shandong, Guangdong, Fujian, Liaoning and some development zones 
attended the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

