<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Phones Mubarak, Al-Asad on Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803052494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0455 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803052494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 17 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton today [17 March] telephoned Egyptian President Husni 
Mubarak and Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad to discuss ways of 
resuming the Mideast peace talks, the White House said. 
  "The President discussed with each leader ways to resume 
negotiations as quickly as possible," White House communications 
director Mark Gearan said in a statement. 
  During the talks with Mubarak and Al-Asad by telephone, 
Clinton described his conversations Wednesday with visiting 
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. 
  Clinton and Rabin Wednesday discussed ways to restart the 
peace talks and called on Palestine Liberation Organization 
(PLO) Chairman Yasir 'Arafat to resume the negotiations 
immediately. 
  The Palestinians broke off the peace talks with Israel after 
the massacre by an Israeli settler of more than 40 Palestinians 
in Hebron two weeks ago. 
  Gearan characterized Clinton's discussions with Mubarak and 
Al-Asad as useful. 

</TEXT>

