<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Germany, Russia To Hold Joint Naval Exercise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003024594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0227 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003024594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, March 9 (XINHUA) -- German and Russian 
defense ministers announced here today that the navies of the 
two countries would stage a joint exercise early this summer in 
the Baltic Sea. 
  German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe and his Russian 
counterpart Pavel Grachev also told a joint press conference 
that a small-scale joint military exercise will be held in 
Russia in 1995 and another in Germany in 1996, to be followed by 
a larger event involving ground troops. 
  Grachev, who arrived in Bonn earlier today for a three-day 
visit, announced that Russia would withdraw all of its remaining 
weapons and ammunition from the former East Germany by the end 
of May this year. 
  The two ministers said they would make efforts to cooperate 
in a regular, planned and long-term manner. 
  Grachev stressed that Russia viewed the proposal 
"Partnership 
for Peace" agreed between the North Atlantic Treaty Organization 
(NATO) and East European countries, as a transitional plan. 
Although Russia would act positively to the NATO proposal it 
was not going to make a hasty political decision on it. 

</TEXT>

