<H3> <TI>   Russia, Latvia Reach Agreement on Troop Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603021394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0114 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603021394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 15 (XINHUA) -- Russia today initialed 
with Latvia an accord on the withdrawal of troops from the 
Baltic state by the end of August. 
  Under the accord, Russia will keep its Skrunda radar station 
in Latvia for four more years and have another 18 months for its 
dismantlement, the ITAR-TASS NEWS AGENCY reported. 
  Chief Russian negotiator Sergey Zotov described the accord 
as 
"a victory for common sense" and said it paved the way for the 
signing of a final agreement probably before mid-April when the 
presidents of the two countries meet. 
  The bulk of the 20,000 ex-Soviet troops in Latvia and 
Estonia 
were stationed in Latvia. Russia completed the withdrawal of 
troops from the third Baltic state of Lithuania last year. 

</TEXT>

