<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Prime Minister Views Upcoming Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1303013694 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1424 
GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1303013694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Yu Yiguo (0205 1355 0948)] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo, 10 Mar (XINHUA) -- This afternoon, Japanese 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who will soon visit China, met 
with Chinese Ambassador to Japan Xu Dunxin at the prime 
minister's official residence. Hosokawa said: The development 
of Japan-China relations is now very smooth in all fields. He 
said he was looking forward to exchanging opinions with Chinese 
leaders on issues of common concern. 
  Touching on the question of economic cooperation between 
Japan and China, Hosokawa expressed his view that Japan and 
China each has its advantageous points, that China's development 
serves the interests of Japan, and that Japan's development is 
also beneficial to China. He hoped the two sides would make 
joint efforts to build a relationship of interdependence and 
make up for each other's deficiencies. 
  During the meeting, Xu Dunxin indicated that the Chinese 
Government attached great importance to Prime Minister 
Hosokawa's forthcoming visit to China and hoped that the prime 
minister's visit would achieve complete success. 

</TEXT>

