<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Rightist' Delegation Arrives in PRC for `Military' Debates </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703104394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1009 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703104394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Osaka, March 17 KYODO -- A group of Japanese 
rightists that has engaged in anti-Chinese campaigns throughout 
Japan arrived in China Thursday [17 March] for eight days of 
meetings with government and research groups, group organizers 
in Osaka said. 
  The delegation, comprised of 16 members of seven nationalist 
organizations in Japan, was invited by a private association 
that promotes exchanges with the Chinese. 
  Organizers in Osaka said it is the first time that 
representatives from more than one nationalist organization have 
been allowed into Communist China at the same time. 
  The members are scheduled to visit Beijing, Dalian and 
Shanghai. They will meet with members of government and research 
bodies to debate China's military growth, the export of military 
weapons and technology, and China's territorial claims to the 
Senkaku Islands located about 160 kilometers north of Yaeyama 
Islands, southwest of Okinawa. 
  The group also will distribute documents outlining arguments 
against the commonly accepted version of the 1937 Nanjing 
massacre, in which more than 142,000 Chinese were killed 
according to estimates made at the Tokyo war crimes trials. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa is scheduled to visit China 
this weekend, but the group's organizers said their visit will 
be different. 
  "We take China seriously. Unlike the present 
administration's apologetic diplomacy, we want to change the 
historical awareness of the last 100 years from the 
Sino-Japanese war, which has been only a discussion in diplomacy 
of assailants and victims," the members said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

