<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Article Views U.S.-DPRK Talks on Nuclear Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1803132194 Beijing RENMIN RIBAO OVERSEAS EDITION in 
Chinese 9 Mar 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> HK1803132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing RENMIN RIBAO OVERSEAS EDITION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Li Nengqing (7812 5174 3237): "Situation on </F>
Korean Peninsula Tends to Relax"] 
  [Text] On 1 March, technical experts sent by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency entered the territory of the 
DPRK and carried out inspections at seven of its nuclear 
facilities. On 3 March, representatives from northern and 
southern Korea resumed contacts between working representatives, 
and they sent special envoys to visit each other, which had been 
suspended for four months. The United States announced the 
resumption of the third round of high-level intergovernmental 
talks with the DPRK on 21 March and conditionally announced the 
suspension of this year's "Team Spirit" exercise. This series 
of dialogues and detente has thrown a new ray of hope on the 
tense and mutually confrontational Korean peninsula. 
  The DPRK announced on 12 March 1993 that it would withdraw 
from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty and decreed that the 
Korean people remained in a "state of semi-war." The United 
States and some Western countries then stated that they would 
impose sanctions on the DPRK. The DPRK, however, announced that 
international sanctions would mean a declaration of war against 
it. With the mediation of some countries, on 2 June, the DPRK 
and the United States held a high-level intergovernmental 
meeting, issued a joint declaration, and agreed on principles 
such as guaranteeing the non-use of nuclear weapons and of armed 
threats, establishing a nuclear-free Korean peninsula, that the 
DPRK and the United States should respect each other's 
sovereignty and not interfere in each other's internal affairs, 
and that the United States supports the reunification of Korea. 
This was the first document reached between the DPRK and the 
United States toward the normalization of relations since they 
stopped fighting 40 years ago. In view of the United States' 
promises, the DPRK announced that it would not withdraw from the 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty temporarily. In mid-July, the 
two sides held a second round of high-level intergovernmental 
talks where the United States promised to supply the DPRK with 
civilian nuclear technology in exchange for its acceptance of 
international nuclear inspections. 
  Nevertheless, the two sides differed in opinion on the form 
and number of nuclear inspections with the result that the 
nuclear inspections could not proceed as scheduled. The two 
sides took opposing attitudes over this question and the 
situation became tense again. 
  At working talks between DPRK and U.S. representatives in 
New 
York last October, the two sides discussed a "basket of 
proposals for the resolution of the nuclear issue." They 
included the question of official U.S. recognition of the DPRK 
and holding a third round of high-level intergovernmental talks. 
As planned, the third round of DPRK-U.S. intergovernmental 
talks should have begun in November or early December last year. 
But on 1 November, with the United States' insistence, the UN 
General Assembly adopted a resolution demanding that the DPRK 
accept nuclear inspections. In mid-November, the ROK and the 
United States carried out joint military exercises. In the face 
of international pressure, the third round of DPRK-U.S. 
intergovernmental talks failed. In late December, UN Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali and Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir 
Bhutto visited the DPRK to mediate. On 29 December, the 
DPRK-U.S. working talks made progress. The United States stated 
that it would suspend South Korean-U.S. "Team Spirit" exercises 
in 1994 while the DPRK also agreed to accept "continuous" 
nuclear inspections. The two sides agreed to create conditions 
for a third round of DPRK-U.S. intergovernmental talks. In 
January, the United States sent nongovernmental personalities to 
visit the DPRK, and U.S. evangelist Billy Graham even passed a 
message from Clinton to Chairman Kim Il-song expressing 
willingness to make efforts to improve DPRK-U.S. relations. 
However, at the same time, the United States sent a team of 
intelligence experts to Seoul to step up monitoring of the DPRK. 
Moreover, it stated that it would deploy Patriot missiles to 
the ROK. 
  On 25 February, an agreement issued by the DPRK and the 
United States announced that the two sides had reached an 
agreement. The United States announced that it had agreed to 
suspend "Team Spirit" exercises with the ROK, while the DPRK 
accepted continuous nuclear inspections intended to safeguard 
nuclear security. They also agreed to resume working contacts 
between northern and southern Korea, which is intended to 
facilitate the mutual dispatch of special envoys and holding a 
third round of DPRK-U.S. talks between high-ranking officials in 
Geneva on 21 March. 
  We must see, however, that in announcing a date for a third 
round of DPRK-U.S. talks and the suspension of the "Team Spirit" 
military exercises, the United States has attached conditions. 
These preconditions were absent from the original agreement 
reached between the DPRK and the United States. The United 
States also stated that if the international inspections were 
unsatisfactory, "Team Spirit" would be resumed. Observers 
maintain that in resolving the nuclear issue on the Korean 
peninsula, they must have good faith or else agreements will 
become empty even if there are many more of them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

