<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   NPC Finance Committee Says Money Supply Must Be Controlled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1803053194 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1324 GMT 
17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1803053194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 17 (CNS)--Chairman of the Financial 
and Economic Committee of the NPC Mr Liu Suinian, delivering a 
report reviewing the plan for last year's national economy and 
social development and this year's draft plan at the meeting of 
the Presidium of the 8th NPC today, said that the central bank 
must be responsible for giving priority to stabilizing the value 
of the renminbi and it would not be allowed to stimulate further 
economic increases by merely issuing more money. 
  The committee put forward seven suggestions in light of the 
recent report on planning work by Minister of the State Planning 
Commission Mr Chen Jinghua. One of the main suggestions dealt 
with attempts to control the size of credit and the supply of 
money. 
  Mr Liu said that China had increased its credit at a high 
speed in the past two years and had increased the issuing of 
money into circulation. If the government did not make up its 
mind to reduce the supply of money, a number of serious problems 
would be created unfavourable to stable economic development. 
  The committee suggested that the banks should greatly 
improve 
their fund management and speed up capital flow, strictly 
restricting and striving to reduce the size of credit. 
  It also suggested greatly strengthening macro-control, 
restricting investment in fixed assets and overgrowth in demand 
of consumer goods, developing the rural economy in an overall 
way, particularly in the production of grain, cotton, vegetable 
oils, meat, sugar and vegetables, strictly controlling prices 
for everyday needs, services and agricultural production means 
and cracking down firmly on criminal acts and misdemeanours 
involving speculation and the raising of prices. 
  With regard to boosting economic results, Mr Liu said that 
China's economic results on the whole remained low with 30 
percent of state-owned enterprises running at a loss. Social 
capital circulated slowly and the debt problem among enterprises 
was becoming increasingly serious. China, therefore, had to 
deepen reform and boost economic results while enterprises with 
serious losses must be declared bankrupt. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

