<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Trade Reform Researcher Sees Adverse Trade Balance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1803054094 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1214 GMT 
17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1803054094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 17 (CNS)--Member of the CPPCC and 
former vice minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation 
Mr. Wei Yuming forecast today that China would continue to have 
an adverse balance of trade this year but that it would be less 
than that of last year. 
  He summarized the following factors adversely affecting an 
increase of Chinese exports this year: 
  --Foreign trade enterprises are lacking circulating capital 
and it will be difficult for them to get bank loans. There will 
also be a shortage of funds for the purchase of goods for export. 
  --The purchasing price for goods for export will increase 
following the price hike in the country. This will affect 
export goods' prices and the confidence of overseas businessmen 
in Chinese commodities. 
  The depressed world economy will lead to a small demand from 
overseas markets. 
  Mr. Wei said that foreign trade enterprises last year had 
achieved more autonomy in their management and had received 
financial aid from banks in the country. China was planning to 
set up banks dealing with import- and export-related business. 
Such things would help meet this year's foreign trade target. 
  Mr. Wei, who is now director of a research group for reform 
of the Chinese foreign trade system, said that the most 
difficult period for reform of the foreign trade system had now 
gone. Difficulties now facing China were how to develop various 
kinds of markets, letting the foreign trade enterprises move 
towards forming large-scale groups and how to prevent a draining 
of talented people from this sector. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

