<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPPCC Member on Hong Kong Political, Economic Systems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803072294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0651 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803072294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 18 (XINHUA) -- The future Hong Kong 
Special Administrative Region (SAR) should follow the principle 
of "one country, two systems" and develop capitalist political 
and economic systems with Hong Kong characteristics, a Hong Kong 
public figure said here today. 
  F. K. Hu, a member of the Eighth National Committee of the 
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference [CPPCC], said 
the SAR should adhere to Hong Kong's existing system and 
encourage local citizens to work hard and build "capitalism with 
Hong Kong characteristics" under the guidance of the 
Sino-British Joint Declaration and the SAR Basic Law. 
  Economically, it is necessary to carry out a laissez-fair 
trade policy and consolidate the open market economic system to 
ensure fair and free competition among investors and 
industrialists, said Hu, chairman of the Hong Kong Ryoden 
Electric Engineering Co., Ltd. 
  In terms of law, the SAR should uphold the spirit of lofty 
fair legislation to boost the confidence of investors, and the 
most important thing in this regard is to protect private 
properties and human rights, he said. 
  The future Hong Kong should also maintain political and 
economic stability, adopt a simple taxation system and build 
infrastructural projects to attract investors, he said. 
  It is imperative to follow the duty-free policy to 
facilitate 
free flow of funds and goods, free investors and businessmen of 
unnecessary worries, and avoid procedures and overheads caused 
by various control measures such as foreign exchange control, he 
said. 
  He suggested that the SAR maintain the existing civil 
service 
system, build housing whose prices are lined with costs and sell 
units to low-income residents; and strengthen education, medical 
care and social security services. 
  Hong Kong and the mainland should expand exchanges, trade 
and 
cooperation, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

