<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPPCC Members Call Attention to Agriculture </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803092694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0843 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 18 (XINHUA) -- Some members of the 
Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political 
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) called on developing 
agriculture, expanding the grain crop growing area, and 
stabilizing grain price. 
  Speaking at the ongoing session of the CPPCC National 
Committee, Li Yongchang, vice-chairman of the Shandong 
Provincial Committee of the Jiu San Society, said that grain 
crops should account for 70 percent of the total acreage and at 
least for 65 percent so as to ensure growth of grain output. 
  Zhu Xiangyuan, director of the Beijing Nutrition Research 
Institute, suggested that the government readjust the grain 
purchasing price, protect interests of grain farmers, support 
and adopt preferential tax policies for commodity grain 
counties. "It is of vital importance for China to maintain the 
per capita grain output at a high level while the population 
continues to increase," he said. 
  Sun Han, vice-chairman of the CPPCC Jiangsu Provincial 
Committee, suggested that China accelerate establishment of 
community economic cooperatives in rural areas and finally set 
up a national network of economic cooperatives. Economically 
developed areas should organize specialized cooperatives to meet 
needs of a market economy. 
  Some CPPCC members said that China should build up a grain 
supply guarantee system to stabilize grain prices. Zhu 
Xiangyuan proposed that the new system consist of three sectors: 
first, establishment of central and local grain reserve centers 
and risk funds; second, supervising grain prices throughout 
China, setting ceiling and bottom prices and stabilizing the 
prices with grain reserve or risk fund when fierce fluctuation 
occurs; and third, assigning relevant institutions to regulate 
grain supply with rational subsidies and rules. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

