<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inner Mongolia Steps Up Development Strategy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203133394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1020 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hohhot, March 2 (XINHUA) -- North China's Inner 
Mongolia Autonomous Region has stepped up implementation of its 
development strategy and a new pattern of opening-up has taken 
shape. 
  The series of preferential policies and deepening of the 
internal reforms of the foreign trade system have effectively 
helped expand the scope of business activities with foreign 
enterprises and regions. 
  By the end of 1993, the number of foreign trade companies, 
border barter-trade companies and export-oriented industrial 
enterprises being granted the managerial rights in imports and 
exports all over the 12 leagues and cities of Inner Mongolia 
exceeded 90, an increase of about 30 percent over the previous 
year. 
  Agency services of the 90-plus privileged economic entities 
have channeled products of thousands of enterprises of Inner 
Mongolia to international markets and introduced foreign 
technology and products to domestic markets. 
  Last year, trade volume of imports and exports of the 
autonomous region reached 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, increasing 
by 28.2 percent over that of the previous year. 
  According to local foreign trade officials, more and more 
foreign investors have recognized the growing importance of 
Inner Mongolia, which set up economic ties with 82 countries and 
regions of the world in the year 1993. 
  Foreign-funded enterprises have mushroomed in fields like 
energy, transportation, machinery, electronics, building 
materials and textiles with capital coming from 31 countries and 
regions including the United States, Russia, Japan and the 
Republic of Korea. 
  International economic and technological cooperation have 
also been expanded. The region has signed contracts for 143 
labor service and construction projects with foreign countries. 
  Domestic enterprises and companies of the Inner Mongolia 
Autonomous Region have also established 83 subsidiaries or joint 
ventures in Russia and Republic of Mongolia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

