<H3> <TI>   Delegation To Attend Pacific Economic Council Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703133094 Taipei CNA in English 1251 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703133094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 17 (CNA) -- A 20-member Taiwan 
delegation will leave for Kuala Lumpur Sunday [20 March] to 
attend the 10th congress of the Pacific Economic Cooperation 
Council (PECC). 
  The congress, which will open March 22 and last for three 
days, will bring together representatives from 26 PECC member 
states, said a spokesman for the Chinese Taipei committee of the 
PECC. 
  The participants will discuss ways to promote regional 
economic cooperation, financial liberalization, opening of 
service markets, and development of aviation and automobile 
industries in the Asia- Pacific region, the spokesman explained. 
  Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad will deliver a 
keynote speech at the opening ceremony. Thai Deputy Prime 
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi and ranking officials from Peru, 
Vietnam, Singapore, Chile, Russia and other countries are 
expected to attend the meeting. 
  The Taiwan delegation, to be headed by Jeffrey Koo, vice 
chairman of the Taipei PECC Committee, will comprise officials, 
scholars and business executives. 
  Founded in 1980, the Canberra-based PECC groups 26 members, 
including Taiwan, Mainland China, Japan, South Korea, the United 
States, New Zealand, Australia, Singapore and Thailand. 

</TEXT>

