<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lu Ping on Not `Rigidly' Adhering to Airport Debt Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1803114794 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 1401 
GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1803114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Xie Zuan (6200 9449): "Lu Ping Says Hong Kong New </F>
Airport Project Talks Should Be Held in Compliance With the 
Memorandum of Understanding"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 17 March (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE)--Lu Ping, 
director of the State Council's Hong Kong and Macao Affairs 
Office, commented today on Hong Kong's new airport to deputies 
from the Hong Kong and Macao region of Guangdong Province to the 
8th National People's Congress. He pointed out that it is the 
consistent stand of the Chinese Government to build a new 
airport in Hong Kong. Despite the fact that the British side has 
once again complicated the issue deliberately, the Chinese side 
still cherishes the hope that the two sides can continue talks 
on the airport in line with the spirit and principle of the 
Memorandum of Understanding on Hong Kong's New Airport, reach an 
agreement at an early date, and strive to start construction of 
the airport as soon as possible. 
  Lu Ping indicated that the aforementioned Memorandum of 
Understanding is a solemn diplomatic document signed by the 
heads of both the Chinese and British Governments; therefore, 
everything should have been fine after the signing of the 
document. However, the British side has asked us to make our 
position known. The Chinese Government has already declared its 
stance, that is, we support the idea of building a new airport 
at low cost and with high efficiency and demand that it brings 
no financial burden to the future government of the Hong Kong 
Special Administrative Region [SAR]. To put it in detailed 
terms, financial reserves of HK$25 billion [Hong Kong dollars] 
should be set aside for the SAR government and the total debt 
borne by the government should not exceed HK$5 billion. Things 
could begin right then if everyone agreed to act in compliance 
with the Memorandum of Understanding. However, the British Hong 
Kong Government later put forward a financial package in which 
liabilities overran by a large margin the provisions in the 
Memorandum of Understanding. The total amount of liabilities 
set out in the first package stood at over HK$70 billion. Lu 
Ping said that the British side must be kidding if it is indeed 
acceptable for the SAR government to undertake debt of over 
HK$70 billion given financial reserves of just HK$25 billion. 
  Lu Ping noted: The British side put forward a third and then 
a fourth financial package, and the latter still falls short of 
the stipulations of the Memorandum of Understanding. Therefore, 
the British side is to blame for a failure to act in accordance 
with the Memorandum of Understanding. The issue is very simple, 
and they can go ahead without holding discussions with us. The 
reason why the British side wants to hold talks with the Chinese 
side is because nothing can be accomplished if they stick to 
this financial package. They will not be able to raise loans. 
Banks will not grant them loans because the financial package 
raised by the British side does not conform to the Memorandum of 
Understanding. 
  Lu Ping added that the British side is making trouble again. 
Despite this, the Chinese side will not rigidly adhere [si qia 
zhu 2984 1595 0145] to the HK$5 billion ceiling, yet hopes the 
British side can consult the Chinese side if debts exceed HK$5 
billion. The problem now is that the gap is too wide. Lu Ping 
said that at the present stage, the Chinese side is still 
prepared to hold talks with the British side and hopes an 
agreement can be reached at an early date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3278 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi053_w_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-053 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Bank of China Prepared for Transition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1803113994 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 0920 GMT 
18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1803113994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 18 (CNS) -- Vice Chairman of the 
Board of Directors of the Bank of China and Director of the Hong 
Kong and Macao Administrative office of the Bank of China, Mr. 
Huang Diyan, speaking today in an exclusive interview with this 
agency, said that the situation in Hong Kong in the next three 
years, the latter transition period of the territory, would be 
more complicated, and a steady transition of the territory and 
maintenance of its prosperity and stability very much relied on 
the efforts of the Chinese people, including those of 
compatriots in the territory. The Bank of China Hong Kong 
Branch had made strict arrangements for its capital, operation 
and management for dealing with any change which would take 
place in the territory. 
  Mr. Huang said that the branch was strengthening its work in 
three ways: first, it will strive to developing itself and make 
itself stronger; second, it will make all preparations such as 
comparatively relaxed conditions for funds arrangement and the 
strengthening of capital circulation; and third, it will unite 
friends, in a broader way, in industrial, commercial and 
financial circles, enhance its cooperation with them and make 
joint efforts with them for a smooth transition of the territory. 
  The branch will, according to the director, issue Hong Kong 
currency on schedule with all preparations needed for this 
matter being ready. The amount of Hong Kong currency to be 
issued from May 2 this year will be HK$3 billion [Hong Kong 
dollars] to HK$6 billion according to demand. 
  Mr. Huang said that since the beginning of the transition 
period, the Bank of China Group had seen rapid development in 
the territory and Hong Kong people's confidence in the group had 
been increasingly enhanced and industrial and commercial 
circles, especially big financial groups, in the territory were 
willing to become more involved with the bank. The bank now had 
over two million customers in Hong Kong. 
  According to Mr. Huang, the Bank of China Group of Hong Kong 
had also seen rapid development of business exchanges with the 
Mainland with over 2,400 items there being directly invested for 
financed by the group for a total of US$9 billion, involving 
items of energy, transport and construction of development 
zones. In addition, the group has also helped Mainland 
enterprises in listing in Hong Kong for the raising of capital. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

