<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Official Says Reorganizing Councils `Legitimate' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603140994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1249 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, March 16 (XINHUA) -- It is only logical 
and legitimate for the Chinese side to reorganize the three-tier 
councils in Hong Kong in accordance with the Basic Law and 
decisions of China's top legislative organ after 1997. 
  This was stated by Zheng Guoxiong, deputy director of the 
Hong Kong branch of the XINHUA NEWS AGENCY, at a seminar on 
Tuesday [15 March], which was attended by advisors on local 
district affairs. 
  Owing to sabotage of the British side, it is impossible to 
implement the so-called "through train" arrangements, which 
allows legislators elected in 1995 to remain in office after 
July 1, 1997, when China resumes the exercise of sovereignty 
over Hong Kong, Zheng said. 
  As part of the framework with which Britain ruled Hong Kong, 
the last district boards, the two municipal councils and the 
Legislative Council under the British administration will surely 
terminate along with the colonialist reign, he stressed. 
  As the transfer of power is approaching, Zheng said, "we 
must 
rely on Hong Kong compatriots, including Hong Kong advisors, to 
make good preparations for works in all fields during the 
transitional period and make every possible effort to keep Hong 
Kong stable and prosperous." 
  During the seminar, many Hong Kong district affairs advisors 
threw their support to a motion, proposed by Cheng Yiu-tong, a 
Hong Kong deputy to the National People's Congress (NPC), and 
agreed by other 30-odd delegates, on the reorganization of the 
three-tier councils. 
  District affairs advisor Fok Ting-hung deems it necessary 
for 
the NPC, which serves as the highest organ of the state power in 
China, to approve the motion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

