<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Firms Said `Partly To Blame' for Hong Kong Land Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1803052094 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 
18 Mar 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> HK1803052094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Chris Yeung in Beijing] </F>
  [Text] Soaring property prices in Hong Kong were 
detrimental to social stability and economic viability, senior 
Chinese official Lu Ping said yesterday. He said 
mainland-funded companies were partly to blame for speculation 
in the property market. The Hong Kong and Macao Affairs 
Office's think-tank would soon look into the problem and study 
ways of maintaining the territory's economic dynamism, said Mr 
Lu. 
  Speaking to a group of Hong Kong deputies to the Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) at a 
closed-door session, Mr Lu said main land-funded firms would be 
stopped from participating in property speculation. He was 
quoted as saying "quite a number" of mainland-funded firms in 
the territory had been speculating and insisted that was not 
good for Hong Kong. Mr Lu said it was unfair to other investors 
because mainland-funded companies were using state funds to make 
profits. "They can push up the prices of property without 
having to bear any responsibility," he said. 
  In a separate meeting with a group of Hong Kong deputies to 
the National People's Congress, Mr Lu said the level of property 
prices had gone beyond what ordinary residents could bear. 
"Many people cannot afford to buy their own flats. This is a 
big problem. It hinges upon people's livelihood. It hinges on 
whether Hong Kong will be able to maintain its status as an 
international financial centre." 
  He said what had made Hong Kong tick over the past decades 
was its low production costs, luring foreign investors. It was 
reported yesterday the international firm, Unisys, is to shift 
its regional centre from Hong Kong to Singapore because of high 
costs in the territory. "This is a big problem," he said. 
  Mr Lu conceded there were various factors behind the surge 
in 
property prices. But he said the Government had the 
responsibility to solve the problem. "If the problem remains 
unresolved, it will affect the post-1997 government and create a 
major burden on it." 
  Mr Lu said the PWC's economic sub-group would soon form a 
team to study the property market. "We will give suggestions to 
the British side. It's a matter for them as to whether to 
accept it. We will also listen to people from all walks of life 
on effective ways to deal with the problem. We will do as much 
as we can." 
  A Hong Kong deputy to the CPPCC, Ho Sai-chu accused some 
property developers of hoarding land in order to seek more 
profits. Mr Ho, a construction company boss, said although 
36,000 flats had been completed last year, only about 28,000 had 
been put on the market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

