<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Says Military Budget Increase To Offset Inflation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703200494 Beijing China Radio International in English to 
Western North America 0400 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1703200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing China Radio International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Current Affairs" program] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Qian Qichen says that although 
China's 1994 military budget looks bigger, the increase in the 
budget is only being made to offset inflation. 
  Qian Qichen made the statement at a press conference in 
Beijing on Wednesday [16 March]. Li Peichun has a highlight. 
  [Begin recording] China will spend about 52 billion yuan 
this year on defense, about 20 percent higher than last year. 
But Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said this doesn't mean China 
is trying to make itself into a regional power. 
  The foreign minister said in 1993 the inflation rate was 13 
percent and is expected to be 10 percent this year. So actual 
military spending remains the same. The foreign minister said 
China's military budget accounts for 1.7 percent of the gross 
domestic product. He said China's military budget is tiny 
compared to other countries, such as the United States and 
Japan. Qian Qichen said this is proof that China is concerned 
about economic development and not about being a military power. 
  The Chinese foreign minister also said he was a bit 
disappointed with his talks with U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher in Beijing last weekend. He said: Although the 
talks produced some agreements on specific measures to eliminate 
problems caused by the human rights issue, China was ready for 
more substantive talks. 
  Qian Qichen said: Beijing invited Christopher in hopes the 
two sides could improve bilateral ties, but the foreign minister 
said there were events just before Christopher's arrival which 
showed that the United States was not being completely sincere. 
The foreign minister said both governments realized that the 
worsening of relations will have adverse effect on their 
economies. Dialogues will continue until June when the Clinton 
administration decides whether or not to renew China's MFN [most 
favored nation] status. Qian Qichen said any specific plan will 
be made in accordance with the wishes of both governments. He 
said neither country should interfere in the other's internal 
affairs. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

