<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Compensation Activists Detained on Eve of Hosokawa Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803062394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0546 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803062394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 18 KYODO -- Several Chinese victims 
of the war with Japan were detained Friday morning [18 March] as 
they approached the Japanese Embassy to deliver a letter seeking 
an apology from Prime Minister Morihiro hosokawa. 
  The elderly Chinese, 60 to 70 years of age, were taken away 
in police vehicles from in front of the Japanese Embassy in 
Beijing's eastern diplomatic area, witnesses said. 
  It was not immediately known where the activists, some of 
them walking with the aid of canes, were taken. 
  Although the contents of the letter are not known, the war 
compensation activists were believed to be seeking an apology 
from the Japanese prime minister who begins a visit to Beijing 
on Saturday and to ask for war compensation for Japanese 
aggression. 
  News of the demonstration began circulating Thursday 
evening, 
leading to speculation that the event was well planned. 
  One middle-aged man, holding a letter with "Hosokawa" 
written 
on it in large letters, arrived at the embassy at 10 A.M. and 
was immediately taken away, witnesses said. Ten minutes later a 
group of elderly men and one woman arrived by minibus and were 
also questioned and taken away by police. 
  The detentions came a week after police rounded up several 
political and labor activists before and during the visit of 
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher last weekend. 
  A Japanese Embassy spokesman said he was unaware of the 
demonstration and knew nothing of the detentions. 
  The Chinese Government has been sensitive to demanding war 
compensation for civilian casualties from Japan as it is afraid 
it could damage the existing good governmental relations. 
  A group of delegates to the ongoing National People's 
Congress, China's parliament, is presently preparing a motion 
demanding war compensation from Japan, but it is not known 
whether the central authorities will approve such a document. 

</TEXT>

