<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shandong Opens Transportation to Outside Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703060194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0509 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703060194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Qingdao, March 17 (XINHUA) -- The transportation 
sector, which was once controlled completely by the government, 
is now opening to domestic and overseas investors in east 
China's Shandong Province. 
  Some 49 percent of the share ownership of the 
3.1-billion-yuan Jinan-Qingdao Expressway -- one of the 
top-class expressways in China -- will be sold to investors from 
both at home and abroad, sources at the ongoing `94 Qingdao 
Trade Fair said today. 
  Meanwhile, a host of transportation development projects, 
including construction of an expressway, four highways and a 
river navigation lane, as well as a harbor, costing some 15 
billion yuan, are also on offer for investment at the fair. 
  Officials of the provincial communications department noted 
that the winning bidders will enjoy a series of preferential 
policies granted by the government. For instance, they will be 
given priority in developing real estate and other related 
sectors. 
  Zhu Zhenchang, head of the department, told a press 
conference that besides that batch of projects, a succession of 
other transportation projects will be opened to outside 
investors in the future. 

</TEXT>

